<P>
REBELS REJECT PEACE PLAN IN MEXICO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dozens of rebel Indian communities in southern Mexico overwhelmingly rejected 
a government peace proposal but voted against renewed violence. 
</P>
<P>
 The Zapatista National Liberation Army, which launched the New Year's Day 
uprising, issued the results in a communique late Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 It said 98% of villagers in the area it controls, in remote southeastern 
Chiapas state, voted against accepting the government offer, which promised 
more government aid to the impoverished region and reforms of the state's 
repressive political system. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead, the announcement said the villagers, mostly descendants of Mayan 
Indians, voted for "a new national dialogue with all the nation's progressive 
forces for democracy, liberty and justice for all Mexicans." 
</P>
