<TEXT>
<P>
 Cycling  
</P>
<P>
 Clay Moseley of Ruidoso, N. M., beat Kent Bostick of Corrales, N. M., for the 
individual time trial gold medal in the U. S. National Cycling Championships at 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
 Moseley trained with Bostick, a former national time trial champion, and 
credits Bostick with helping him make the team. 
</P>
<P>
 Rebecca Twigg, a Seattle native now living in Flagstaff, Ariz., won the 
women's gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
 Eugeni Berzin, who took the lead in the fourth stage and held it the rest of 
the way, became the first Russian to win the Tour of Italy cycling race. Berzin 
finished two minutes and 51 seconds ahead of runner-up Marco Pantani of Italy. 
Miscellany  
</P>
<P>
 Hortencia scored 27 points in her final international game as Brazil beat 
China, 96-87, to win the women's world basketball championship at Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
 Teresa Edwards scored 20 points to lead the United States to a 100-95 victory 
over Australia in the bronze-medal game. 
</P>
<P>
 Jamaica's Greg Haughton defeated Butch Reynolds in the 400 meters at an 
international track and field meet at Duisburg, Germany. Haughton finished in 
45.54, compared to 46.18 for Reynolds. 
</P>
<P>
 Curling became the 41st sport to be given full recognition by the U. S. 
Olympic Committee. 
