<HEADLINE>
<P>
WOMAN IN PARKED CAR SLAIN AS SHE HOLDS BABY; CRIME: STRAY BULLET HITS SHOPPER 
AS SUSPECTED GANG MEMBER FIRES AT RIVALS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIO MORAN, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Rene Hurtado's 18-month-old daughter was crying when Hurtado returned to her 
car after making a quick purchase late Saturday night at a North Hills 
convenience store. 
</P>
<P>
 Her sister-in-law and 18-month-old niece were also waiting in the car. 
Climbing into the driver's seat, Hurtado, 22, turned and picked up her daughter 
to quiet her before driving away. 
</P>
<P>
 Then the shooting began. Without warning, a suspected gang member began firing 
at a group of rival gang members across the parking lot near Plummer Street and 
Van Nuys Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 One of the bullets slammed through the windshield of Hurtado's car, striking 
her in the chest and just missing her daughter. 
</P>
<P>
 Hurtado's sister-in-law, Brenda Wong, raced to Holy Cross Medical Center in 
Mission Hills, where Hurtado, of Panorama City, was pronounced dead at 10:25 
p.m., Van Nuys Division Police Sgt. Harry Rosenfeld said. 
</P>
<P>
 Wong and the two toddlers were not injured. 
</P>
<P>
 "The woman was holding her daughter and the bullet apparently just missed the 
little girl," Rosenfeld said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police could provide little information about Hurtado on Sunday. Wong and 
other family members gathered at Wong's North Hills apartment Sunday but 
declined to discuss the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
 Rosenfeld said officers spoke to a witness at the scene and have a description 
of the gunman. Police on Sunday suggested that they may have identified a 
suspect, but would not release more information. 
</P>
<P>
 Tom Haddad, owner of Regal Liquor Market and Deli, said he heard about 10 
shots after Hurtado left his store Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 "First there was about five shots, and then I heard another five shots," 
Haddad said Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
 The only visible sign of shooting Sunday was broken glass in the parking lot 
where Hurtado's car had been parked. 
</P>
<P>
 Haddad said that after making her purchase and leaving the store, Hurtado had 
returned to get some change. 
</P>
<P>
 "Maybe if she hadn't come back for change, she would have left before the 
shooting started and she wouldn't have been shot," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Times correspondent Eric Slater contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
