<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; ILLINOIS; AMA CHOOSES FIRST BLACK PRESIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The American Medical Assn. chose the first black in its 147-year history to be 
the group's president-elect. Dr. Lonnie R. Bristow, an internist from San 
Pablo, Calif., will take on the largely speech-making role a year from 
now.Bristow is now chairman of the AMA board and its only black member. He said 
race will not define his role "because, quite simply, it has not happened once 
in all the years that have been leading up to today." Bristow was unopposed for 
president-elect at the AMA convention in Chicago. 
</P>
